<TEXT>
supreme court justice william j brennan 
resigned friday after a 34year career as a leading voice of 
liberalism on the nations highest court 
brennan 84 said his advancing age and medical condition 
led to his decision to step down 
his departure gives president bush his first chance to name a 
justice to the court which has been deeply divided in recent years 
on such issues as a womans right to an abortion affirmative 
action and separation of church and state brennan has been a firm 
advocate of all three 
bush told reporters that brennans decision had taken him by 
surprise 
obviously his resignation is accepted i also thank him for 
his distinguished service to the united states the president 
told reporters aboard air force one en route to washington from 
wyoming 
bush said he would meet with top aides saturday morning to 
start the process of finding a successor and already outside 
groups were seeking to influence his decision the president said 
that he wanted the bestqualified person for the post and was not 
afraid of starting a nomination fight 
the president called brennan during the flight said white house 
spokesman marlin fitzwater fitzwater declined to say what was said 
in the conversation 
an antiabortion group in iowa looked forward to a new justice 
who opposes abortion while eleanor smeal former president of the 
national organization of women said a potential justices views on 
the subject will be the key political issue of the 1990 
senatorial elections 
whatever the course of the confirmation process brennans 
brethren on the court rushed to praise him 
justice thurgood marshall said brennan has been a voice of 
caution and compassion in urging that this court not retreat from 
its constitutional mission to protect individuals rights of 
freedom and expression guarantee that minorities be free from 
discrimination and to assure the rights of those accused of 
crimes 
justice byron r white a member of the high court since 1962 
said i enjoyed every day i spent with him he is a great justice 
and he will be remembered for that 
sen edward m kennedy hailed brennan appointed by president 
eisenhower in 1956 as one of the greatest justices the country 
has ever had 
last april just days before his 84th birthday brennan said he 
was not dismayed by the courts growing conservatism and said would 
not retire unless his health required it 
im not discouraged to the point of giving up he said 
im not going to walk out and say the hell with it 
but brennan suffered a small stroke after the term ended 
falling down in newark airport en route to a scandinavian vacation 
said court spokeswoman toni house his doctor advised brennan to 
avoid stress and strain and consider retiring ms house said 
in his letter to bush brennan said strenuous demands of 
court work and its related duties required or expected of a justice 
appear at this time to be incompatible with my advancing age and 
medical condition 
i therefore retire effectively immediately as an associate 
justice of the supreme court of the united states 
brennan suffered a small stroke in 1979 that left his right arm 
and hand partially paralyzed and in 1978 underwent radiation 
treatments for a cancerous tumor in his throat 
he had said he considered retiring in 1979 burdened also by the 
illness of his wife of 51 years his wife marjorie died of cancer 
in 1982 and brennan subsequently married his secretary of 25 
years mary fowler 
after his appointment by eisenhower brennan quickly found a 
home among the liberal majority led by chief justice earl warren 
along with fellow liberal justice marshall brennan has 
maintained that the constitution forbids the death penalty as cruel 
and unusual punishment 
among the more than 1200 opinions authored by brennan are 
landmarks that imposed a onperson onevote standard for 
electing state legislatures created constitutional protections for 
libel lawsuit defendants and helped invent a legal definition of 
obscenity 
he remains among four justices on the court who wholeheartedly 
support the courts 1973 ruling that legalized abortion nationwide 
brennan said in a statement friday that his retirement is a 
very difficult decision after almost 34 years of service on the 
court 
it is my hope that the court during my years of service has 
built a legacy of interpretation of the constitution and federal 
laws to make them responsive to the needs of the people whom they 
were intended to benefit and protect this legacy can and will 
withstand the test of time 
brennan served under eight presidents his departure is bound to 
cause a dramatic change in the liberalconservative balance at the 
court 
only one justice in the courts history william o douglas 
wrote more opinions only three served at a more advanced age 
oliver wendell holmes 91 roger taney 87 and hugo black 85 
for more than three decades brennan has been a leading exponent 
of liberalism and by most accounts a leading behindthescenes 
strategist in helping mold liberal rulings and in later years in 
preserving them on an increasingly conservative court 
although the court and its changing cast of justices grew more 
conservative over the years he remained a powerful force 
conservatives have consolidated their power and in most cases 
command a 54 majority but in several key areas liberals led by 
brennan have been able to win important victories 
just last month with brennan wrote for a fivemember majority 
that upheld the federal governments power to implement affirmative 
action the court upheld policies of the federal communications 
commission giving minorities special preference in the award of 
broadcast licenses 
brennans health has generally appeared good despite his 
advancing age he was weakened badly by the flu this year but he 
appeared to have recovered by the end of the term last month 
at the time of his appointment he was a member of the new 
jersey supreme court he was confirmed by the senate early in 1957 
with only sen joseph mccarthy rwis voting against him 
mccarthy accused brennan of being too soft on communism 
a graduate of the university of pennsylvania and harvard law 
school he had practiced labor law in newark before becoming a 
state judge in 1949 and rising through the judicial ranks 
</TEXT>
