<TEXT>
president bush thanked retiring justice 
william j brennan on friday for his distinguished service in 
34 years on the bench and said he would meet with advisers saturday 
to begin choosing a successor 
brennans colleagues remembered him as a voice of caution and 
compassion whose decisions over 34 years fought to preserve the 
liberties of americans 
i greet the news of my brother justice brennans departure 
from the court with deep regret justice thurgood marshall said 
in a statement he is an eminent jurist whom no one can equal for 
his breadth of knowledge integrity and commitment to justice for 
all humankind 
without doubt his opinions will go down in history as the 
greatest of the courts 
marshall was perhaps brennans closest collaborator on the 
court both for example opposed the death penalty in all 
circumstances they voted to stop the execution of a virginia man 
thursday night but were outweighed by their colleagues 
chief justice william h rehnquist said brennan has made a 
major contribution to american constitutional law i hope his 
retirement will enable him to relax from the cares of office and 
restore his health 
bush who received a facsimile of brennans resignation as he 
boarded air force one in wyoming said the announcement came as a 
complete surprise 
the matter is now official and we will now start the process 
of finding a successor bush said adding that he would meet 
saturday at the white house with attorney general dick thornburgh 
chief of staff john sununu and white house counsel c boyden gray 
to discuss a successor 
asked what judicial philosophy he would seek bush said its 
too early to express anything of that nature ive always said i 
want somebody who will be on there not to legislate from the bench 
but to faithfully interpret the constitution so that gives me a 
wide latitude 
sen edward kennedy dmass a member of the senate judiciary 
committee ranked brennan with marshall and former justices oliver 
wendell holmes jr and louis brandeis as the greatest justices 
this country ever had 
brennan at 84 was the oldest justice and with more than 33 years 
on the court was the senior in point of service 
i am justice brennans oldest colleague on the court and i 
enjoyed every day i spent with him justice byron white said 
marshall called him a treasured colleage and a dear friend i 
will miss his warm heart and kindred spirit 
justice brennan consistently has been a voice of caution and 
compassion in urging that this court not retreat from its 
constitutional mission to protect individuals rights he added 
american civil liberties union president norman dorsen said 
brennans resignation would be an incalculable loss to the law 
and civil liberties and to every person whose rights are threatened 
in the united states 
justice brennan has been a courageous insightful and above 
all humane jurist he will not be easily replaced 
brennans replacement was the subject of immediate speculation 
and jockeying by interest groups friday night 
kate michelman president of the national abortion rights action 
league said friday was a very very dark day 
ive been saying for months that the threat to our right to 
choose is as close as the next supreme court appointment she 
said in an interview clearly this is a very serious loss for all 
of us who value individual liberty and privacy rights 
the iowa right to life committee however said the 
appointment of one more justice who believes that all human life 
both born and unborn deserves protection will be the beginning 
toward our country once again protecting preborn life 
the court has been split 54 recently on such heated political 
issues as abortion and legal experts predicted the balance was 
about to shift 
sen paul simon dill a member of the judiciary committee 
said that because of the frequent 54 votes brennans resignation 
is a monumental change it is important that president bush make 
an appointment that will not polarize the nation 
susan low bloch a law professor at georgetown university said 
a lot of the 54 decisions that went the way brennan voted are 
likely to switch because i think its likely that president bush is 
going to pick someone whose views differ from brennan 
</TEXT>
