<TEXT>
the air force has told congress it needs 
another 14 billion to acquire two b2 bombers on schedule an 
admission bound to further erode congressional support for the 
radarevading aircraft 
air force secretary donald b rice notified house armed services 
chairman les aspin dwis of the budget shortfall in a letter 
obtained by the associated press over the weekend it came on the 
eve of a speech monday by aspin in which congressional sources 
say he will propose canceling the b2 program entirely 
aspin who kept the increasingly expensive plane alive with 
compromise legislation last year has been moving towards halting 
funds for the program because of its high cost which has 
skyrocketed to about 860 million each 
the pricetag may surpass the 1 billion mark based on the latest 
revelations 
proponents of house legislation to limit the program to the 
planes currently in production say they are a handful of votes 
short of the number needed for approval 
but the plane still has staunch support in the senate where the 
chairman of the senate armed services committee sam nunn dga 
is a key proponent 
rice in his letter dated july 11 said that without the 14 
billion acquisition of the two bombers will have to be delayed 
until 1997 the two b2s are among 15 bombers intended to be bought 
through 1990 at a cost of 27 billion the air force had begun 
procurement of the two planes in 1988 and 1989 
rice also said that the cost of buying two other b2s and 
related items in the 1991 fiscal year beginning oct 1 will total 
46 billion an increase of about 500 million from the original 
figure 
rice blamed the increase in costs primarily on a jump in 
overhead charges and changes in the production rate 
defense secretary dick cheney facing economic pressure and a 
lessening soviet threat in april revised plans for the b2 
cutting the total number of aircraft planned from 132 to 75 and the 
1990 budget request from five to two 
rice said cheneys revision pushed the shortfall to an estimated 
14 billion 
this shortfall will become a liability when the contracts 
are signed and executed rice said in the letter initialing of the 
contracts is expected in december 1990 and the summer of 1991 
the air force examined several options to make up the shortfall 
including using unobligated money from past years or supplemental 
appropriations the service has decided to restructure the previous 
years purchases of 15 planes 
this restructure would involve moving two aircraft to fiscal 
1997 one from fiscal 1988 and one from fiscal 1989 rice 
said 
thus instead of the air forces current plans for 15 planes to 
be bought through 1990 at a cost of about 27 billion the air 
force would be left with 13 planes 
rice said the b2 is not unique to this type of shortfall as 
program costs react to changes in quantity or schedule 
