<TEXT>
gov jim florio standing near new 
jerseys most polluted waterway saturday signed into law a package 
of bills designed to combat water pollution and which would 
penalize violators by up to 10 million 
the governor signed the six bills at the elizabeth marina on the 
arthur kill a shipping channel separating new jersey from new york 
city into which 40000 gallons of oil spilled wednesday 
more than 1 million gallons of oil have spilled into the kill 
and nearby kill van kull this year 
its not going to be business as usual any more said 
florio flanked by legislators who sponsored the measures these 
laws carry a very simple message you spill you pay 
assemblyman robert smith a sponsor of the one of the bills 
said there is an attitude among many corporate executives in the 
oil industry that it is cheaper to pollute than to take 
responsible preventative actions 
the executive director of the new jersey petroleum council an 
industry group issued a statement saying oil companies shared 
florios and the legislatures concern about oil spills 
many of the measures are already being implemented said 
james e benton however legislation that would impose a 10 
million fine for major spills could ultimately have a detrimental 
impact on energy supplies during periods of peak demand consumer 
prices and jobs in new jersey 
florio dismissed concerns about a loss of jobs 
the question is costs versus costs the status quo in this 
process is not cost free it costs each and every person florio 
said one of the spills resulted in parts of the jersey shore 
being closed anyone who thinks that is cost free they are 
misled 
the new laws which take effect over the next two years would 
require protective booms be placed in the water whenever there 
is a transfer of oil or hazardous liquid from ship to shore or ship 
to ship 
impose tougher standards on companies storing and transferring 
hazardous substances 
require all pipelines in new jersey to be mapped and 
registered 
mandate special lighting be in place whenever pipeline 
transfers are done at night 
the last two provisions grew out of the exxon pipeline rupture 
on jan 1 that spewed more 567000 gallons of home heating oil into 
the arthur kill a coast guard investigation concluded in part that 
the spill was so extensive because workers were pumping oil through 
the pipeline at night and could not tell it was leaking into the 
waterway 
if spills do occur the new laws also pose tougher penalties of 
up to 10 million for spills of 100000 gallons or more of a 
hazardous substance the penalties would apply to any spills that 
reach new jersey waters or lands regardless of where they 
originate 
companies would not be able to deduct the costs of cleanups or 
fines from state taxes under the new laws 
the state department of environmental protection would also be 
able to assess civil penalties directly rather than having to go 
to court to collect billable costs would be expanded to include 
the cost of restoring or replacing personal property lost income 
resulting from damage caused by a spill and the cost of repairing 
or replacing damaged and destroyed natural resources 
the previous law provided only for penalties of up to 50000 a 
day and did not take into account the size of the spill 
