dr arthur t hertig whose research on 
embryos helped lead to the development of the birthcontrol pill 
and testtube fertilization has died at age 86 
hertig died friday at falmouth hospital of cardiac arrest after 
colon surgery said his son andrew 
the lexington researcher was known for his work with fetuses 
less than two weeks old at harvard medical school between 1938 and 
1952 
a fellow researcher dr john rock later developed the 
birthcontrol pill the work also laid the foundation for 
infertility therapy and for the successful transplantation of 
fertilized eggs 
hertig a gynecological pathologist also studied ovarian 
tumors gynecological cancers and miscarriages 
after 37 years at the medical school hertig resigned in 1970 to 
study the morphology of primate ovaries at the new england regional 
primate research center in southborough he resigned three years 
ago 
a native of minnesota hertig graduated from the university of 
minnesota in 1928 he graduated from harvard medical school two 
years latre 
in 1979 hertig received the goldheaded cane award from the 
american association of pathologists which cited him as a 
physician who represents the highest ideals in medicine and 
pathology 
