<TEXT>
the pepper commission a group created by 
congress to study health insurance problems will recommend that 
the federal government pay basic medicare costs for the 35 million 
elderly people whose income is below the poverty line about 
6000 for an individual according to a published report 
the panel also will recommend that the government help pay 
medicare costs for an additional 82 million elderly people whose 
incomes are up to twice the poverty level the washington post 
reported in sundays editions 
those and other recommendations adopted by the panel friday 
would cost the government about 28 billion a year the paper said 
medicare is the health care program for the elderly and costs 
each recipient 343 a year in premiums if they are enrolled in the 
part of the program that pays a portion of outofhospital 
expenses in addition beneficiaries must pay the first 592 for 
each hospital stay and a portion of hospital stays that extend 
beyond 60 days 
the commission is headed by sen john d rockefeller iv 
dwva and named for the late rep claude pepper dfla 
in an earlier report the panel outlined a plan for longterm 
care for the elderly and suggested that all employers be required 
to provide policies to workers or contribute to a government backup 
plan for those not covered through their jobs 
an estimated 31 million americans have no health insurance 
the post said 12 of the 15 commission members have agreed to the 
medicare proposals for the poor elderly the paper said the panel 
did not hold a formal meeting but that the proposals were 
circulated to the members who responded with their approval or 
disapproval 
the paper quoted unidentified sources as saying the tally was 
completed friday 
